# Workspace context — example template

Copy this file to `/etc/mwmai/obsidian-context.md` on the VPS and fill in
with concise, model-facing facts about *your* workspace. The responder
loads it once per invocation and prepends it to every Groq/Ollama prompt,
so the model answers notes questions with project-aware grounding instead
of generic advice.

Keep it **under ~3 KB**. Short bullet lists beat paragraphs. Treat this
file as something the model reads — not as documentation for humans.

**This file is not in git.** Write the real one directly on the VPS with
mode 0644 and include personal/private details. The repo only ships this
template so others know the shape.

---

## Identity

- Name, role, location (short — e.g. "Alex, indie dev, Berlin")
- Time zone (so the model answers with correct dates/times)

## Active projects

- `project-a` — one-line purpose, live URL, current status
- `project-b` — ...
- `project-c` — ...

(List every project the model should recognize by name. Include state:
LIVE / WIP / PAUSED / PLANNED. Do not list archived projects.)

## Tech stack

- Languages: Python 3.11, Go 1.22, ...
- Frameworks: FastAPI, ...
- Infra: Docker Compose, VPS X at Y, ...
- Data: Postgres 16, Redis, ...
- LLMs: Groq (free tier) primary, Ollama llama3.1:8b fallback

## Coding conventions

- Python: f-strings, Pathlib, specific exceptions, type hints required on public APIs
- JS/TS: ...
- Never commit: .env files, credentials, cloud keys
- Git: conventional commits, squash-merge PRs

## Repositories

- `github.com/<user>/<repo-a>` — public
- `github.com/<user>/<repo-b>` — private

## Operational facts the model should know

- Backups run at 01:00 UTC nightly to /mnt/backup
- The main dev machine is Pop!_OS 24.04
- Secrets live in /etc/mwmai/*.env (mode 0600)
- Syncthing mesh: workstation ↔ VPS ↔ phone

## How to answer

- When the user asks about "the X project", they mean the one from the
  "Active projects" list above — do not invent new project names.
- Default to markdown lists. No emojis unless asked.
- If a question references a file path, assume paths are on the
  workstation (Linux, home at /home/<user>/) unless explicitly VPS.
- For code snippets: complete, runnable, stdlib-first.
- When unsure: say so briefly, ask one clarifying question, stop.
